05383nam a22007095i 9781580467322DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815804673227 a10.1515/97815804673222doi  a(DE-B1597)675769  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a271.973045422231 aWatt, Jeffrey R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Scourge of Demons :bPossession, Lust, and Witchcraft in a Seventeenth-Century Italian Convent /cJeffrey R. Watt.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2009] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b5 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChanging Perspectives on Early Modern Europe ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION Nuns, Witchcraft, and the Inquisition -- tChapter 1 FEMALE RELIGIOUS, CLAUSTRATION, AND SANTA CHIARA OF CARPI -- tChapter 2 THE OUTBREAK AND MALEFICIA -- tChapter 3 THE CONFESSOR AND LOVE MAGIC -- tChapter 4 THE EXORCISTS AND THE DEMONS -- tChapter 5 SISTERS DEALTA AND IPPOLITA UNDER ATTACK -- tChapter 6 BELLACAPPA’S DEFENSE -- tChapter 7 THE WANING OF THE POSSESSIONS -- tCONCLUSION -- tAPPENDIX A -- tAPPENDIX B Time Line of the Holy Office’s Investigation of the Santa Chiara Case -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA fascinating examination of alleged demon possession and witchcraft in a seventeenth-century convent in Carpi, Italy.In 1636, residents at the convent of Santa Chiara in Carpi in northern Italy were struck by an extraordinary illness that provoked bizarre behavior. Eventually numbering fourteen, the afflicted nuns were subject to screaming fits,throwing themselves on the floor, and falling abruptly into a deep sleep. When medical experts' cures proved ineffective, exorcists ministered to the women and concluded that they were possessed by demons and the victims of witchcraft. Catering to women from elite families, the nunnery suffered much turmoil for three years and, remarkably, three of the victims died from their ills. A maverick nun and a former confessor were widely suspected to be responsible, through witchcraft, for these woes. Based primarily on the exhaustive investigation by the Inquisition of Modena, The Scourge of Demons examines this fascinating case in its historical context. The travails of Santa Chiara occurred at a time when Europe witnessed peaks in both witch-hunting and in the numbers of people reputedly possessed by demons. Female religious figures appeared particularly prone to demonic attacks, and Counter-Reformation Church authorities were especially interested in imposing stricter discipline on convents. Watt carefully considers how the nuns of Santa Chiara understood and experienced alleged possession and witchcraft, concluding that Santa Chiara's diabolical troubles and their denouement -- involving the actions of nuns, confessors, inquisitorial authorities, and exorcists -- were profoundly shaped by the unique confluence of religious, cultural, judicial, andintellectual trends that flourished in the 1630s. Jeffrey R. Watt is professor of history at the University of Mississippi.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCarpi (Italy) -- Church history -- 17th century. 0aDemoniac possession -- Italy -- Carpi -- History -- 17th century. 0aDemoniac possessionzItalyzCarpixHistoryy17th century. 0aMonastero Santa Chiara (Carpi, Italy) -- History -- 17th century. 0aWitchcraft -- Italy -- Carpi -- History -- 17th century. 0aWitchcraftzItalyzCarpixHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History